   <mods:abstract>Has received letter and pamphlet; "I shall peruse it with attention and
            form my opinion of it with Candour." [Apparently a pun.] Can understand the mental
            strain under which Jenings was because of the Laurens affair, and feels that no
            forgiveness should be asked under the circumstances. He certainly would not ascribe
            Jenings' failure to call to neglect. Had they discussed this in London, Jenings would
            have gotten the same impression Jay conveyed in Paris; that is, that it is not wise to
            discuss such a matter with either of the parties. Rather he [Jay] would follow the
            "Golden Rule"--"to do as we in such Situations wish to be done by-", and hear and
            examine carefully to determine the truth.</mods:abstract>
